'''Mito Shrine''' (みとじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kashima-ku|Q24895757|qid=Q24895757|1=Kashima-ku}}, {{ill|lt=Minamisōma|Q642094|qid=Q642094|1=Minamisōma}}, {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707|qid=Q71707|1=Fukushima Prefecture}}.
Its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=old ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was village shrine. It is one of eight Engishiki-listed shrines in Namekata District{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=of Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Enshrines {{ill|qid=Q1107286|lt=Futsunushi-no-Kami|Q1107286|qid=Q1107286|1=Futsunushi}}.
** The Sōma-domain history '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōsōshi|1=UNKNOWN}}' says Susanoo-no-Mikoto, but shrine tradition says this may be a record error confusing the deity of '''Yasaka Shrine''', a precinct shrine of Mito Shrine.

=== Origin ===
It is said that in the era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|qid=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}}, when {{ill|lt=Yamato Takeru|Q461258|qid=Q461258|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru}} campaigned eastward, the deity was invited here. In {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|qid=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} 5 ({{ill|lt=905|Q24239|qid=Q24239|1=905}}), Mito Shrine was listed among 100 Engishiki shrines of {{ill|lt=Mutsu Province|Q907389|qid=Q907389|1=Mutsu Province}} as a shrine with spiritual efficacy for protection of the state. In {{ill|lt=Kanki|Q1194200|qid=Q1194200|1=Kangi}} 1 (1229), the Namekata clan rebuilt shrine buildings and donated sacred fields; in {{ill|lt=Shōtoku|Q1193848|qid=Q1193848|lt=Shōtoku|1=Shōtoku (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1712|Q6871|qid=Q6871|1=1712}}), lord {{ill|lt=Sōma Takatane|Q8515901|qid=Q8515901|1=Sōma Takatane}} of {{ill|lt=Sōma Nakamura Domain|Q844079|qid=Q844079|1=Sōma Nakamura Domain}} donated 5 koku 3 shō. It was thus revered by both domain lords and local people. In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 11 it was designated village shrine.

The enshrined deity is traditionally identified as martial deity Futsunushi-no-Kami of {{ill|lt=Katori Jingū|Q372380|qid=Q372380|1=Katori Jingū}} in {{ill|lt=Chiba Prefecture|Q80011|qid=Q80011|1=Chiba Prefecture}}. As seen in place name "Kenmiya" and shrine name, it is a shrine of the "sword," and records say the {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|qid=Q327532|1=Shintai}} is an "ancient sword of a thousand years."

Standing near the sea amid rice fields, Mito Shrine was hit by the great tsunami of the {{ill|lt=2011|Q1994|qid=Q1994|1=2011}} {{ill|lt=March 11|Q2398|qid=Q2398|1=March 11}} {{ill|lt=Tohoku earthquake and tsunami|Q36204|qid=Q36204|1=2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami}}. The sacred grove remained, but torii, shrine buildings, and precinct shrines were swept away, and many nearby parishioner homes were also lost. After the disaster, restoration projects were carried out with support from shrine offices of various prefectures; with backing from {{ill|lt=Hokkaidō Shrine Office|Q135249444|qid=Q135249444|1=Hokkaido Prefectural Shrine Association}} and {{ill|lt=Shitaya Shrine|Q11361339|qid=Q11361339|1=Shitaya Shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|qid=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}, a temporary shrine building was erected in the precinct on June 11. The "image of Susanoo-no-Mikoto," shintai of precinct Yasaka Shrine, was also found in the rubble.

